**Spain Exceeds Deadline for Approving Directive on Transparent and Predictable Working Conditions**
Spain is about to exceed the two-year deadline for approving the directive on transparent and predictable working conditions, which was adopted in 2019. The directive aims to end practices that have led to precarious work, such as flexible contracts and short-term employment. The Spanish government included the measure in its electoral program, but it has been delayed due to internal conflicts and negotiations with social partners. The anteproyecto de ley was approved on February 6, but it has been debated and amended in the parliamentary committee, with some sources claiming that there has been no progress in negotiations. The project aims to ensure that workers have clear information about their job, including contract duration, working hours, and trial periods. It also establishes rules for changing contracts, notice periods, and the right to request job openings. The text has been criticized for being too weak and not addressing the main issues of precarious work.
