**Crisis Over 2030 World Cup Stadiums in Spain, Portugal, and Morocco**
A crisis has emerged regarding the stadiums that will host the 2030 World Cup in Spain, Portugal, and Morocco. According to Marca, a Spanish newspaper, the meeting in Agadir, Morocco, did not yield any new developments, as no agreement or stadium selection was made. Valencia's Mestalla stadium has requested to host some matches, but it is unclear if this request was submitted on time. The path is long and tense, especially since the necessary steps must be taken to select the stadiums before July 31, 2024. The Spanish government's sustainable development committee, led by Prime Minister Juan Maria Fernández-Carriedo, has proposed that Spain have more than 11 stadiums, considering the 12 candidates who submitted their documents, but no agreement was reached between Morocco and Portugal. FIFA initially did not want to exceed 20 stadiums, which led to doubts at the Agadir meeting, despite sources from the sustainable development committee stating that FIFA agreed to expand as long as Portugal and Morocco wanted. It appears that Mestalla has been excluded, but Valencia has made a last-minute proposal that is not yet decisive to be part of the project, pending the city council's approval and the withdrawal of some requests, such as the creation of a shopping center in the stadium. The closest stadiums so far are Camp Nou, Espanyol, San Mamés, Real Arena, Santiago Bernabéu, La Cartuja, Metropolitano, Romaneda, Rosaleda, Gran Canaria, and Riazor, while the stadiums in Murcia and Xixón have been excluded, with the possibility of adding six stadiums from Morocco and three from Portugal.
