**Crisis Over 2030 World Cup Stadiums: No Agreement Reached**
According to Spanish newspaper Marca, there is a crisis regarding the stadiums that will host the 2030 World Cup in Spain, Portugal, and Morocco. The meeting held in Agadir, Morocco, did not yield any new developments, as no agreement or decision was made on the stadiums. Valencia's Mestalla stadium has requested to host some matches, but it's unclear if this request was made on time. The path is long and tense, especially since the necessary steps must be taken to determine the stadiums before July 31, 2024. The Spanish government's sustainable development committee, represented by Juan Maria Fernández-Carriedo, proposed that Spain have more than 11 stadiums, considering the 12 candidates who submitted their documents. However, no agreement was reached between Morocco and Portugal. Initially, FIFA did not want to exceed 20 stadiums, which led to the doubts raised in the Agadir meeting. According to sources, FIFA agreed to expand the number of stadiums as long as Portugal and Morocco wanted. It appears that Mestalla has been excluded, but Valencia has made a last-minute proposal that is not yet decisive. The closest stadiums so far are Camp Nou, Estadi de Espanyol, San Mamés, Real Arena, Santiago Bernabéu, La Cartuja, Metropolitano, Romareda, Rosaleda, Gran Canaria, and Riazor, while stadiums in Murcia and Gijón have been excluded, with the possibility of adding six Moroccan and three Portuguese stadiums.
