**Aena improves its forecasts and will exceed 300 million passengers this year**
Aena, the national airport authority, has improved its estimates of passenger traffic growth by 4.5 points, from a central scenario of 3.8% to 8.3%. This is due to the evolution of data at Spanish airports during the first five months of the year. The consecutive records of passenger traffic month by month at most facilities have led Aena to revise its estimates upwards. As a result, Aena expects that this year will exceed 300 million passengers, with a figure of around 306.7 million, according to its calculations. 'The traffic in 2024 is behaving better than expected due to the strong and constant demand', they express. The company, led by Maurici Lucena, points to the high number of seats programmed by airlines, the improvement in economic prospects in Spain, and the level of demand from major emitting countries as reasons that explain this 'predictable surge in air traffic'. During the first five months of the year, Aena has seen a 11.4% increase in passenger traffic at its facilities compared to the same period last year.
