**Spain's Public Employment Offer Exceeds 40,000 Positions for 2024**
The Spanish government has presented a public employment offer of over 40,000 positions for this year, a slightly higher number than the 39,574 published in the Official State Gazette (BOE) last year. The offer includes positions in the central government, the armed forces, and security forces, but not those of autonomous communities or municipalities. The government aims to present the final list of positions to the next Council of Ministers, which could happen on June 25. The proposal has generated more dissatisfaction than satisfaction among the negotiating unions, with CCOO and Csif opposing it, while UGT has expressed satisfaction with the number of positions. The offer includes 20,840 positions for open competition and at least 10,600 for internal promotion, as well as 6,520 for the armed forces and 2,161 for internal promotion. CCOO has criticized the slow pace of execution of the competitions, which has led to thousands of positions being lost since 2019, reducing the estimated net employment creation. The offer is the highest ever and includes at least 3,000 positions from previous years that have not been filled. The government plans to change the law to eliminate the 10% reserve for people with disabilities and the 2% for people with intellectual disabilities. The minister has also announced plans to eliminate the employment replacement rate, which limits the number of positions that can be offered each year, and replace it with a new system that will allow for more flexible hiring. The government's decision to not present new budgets and prolong the existing ones has had various consequences, including the delay of the public employment offer and the freezing of public employee salaries. The salary increase, which is already agreed upon, will be retroactive to January 1, but it is still pending legislative approval.
