**Spain Avoids EU Deficit Sanctions, But Warned of Fiscal Rule Breach**
The European Commission has decided not to launch a procedure to punish Spain for exceeding the 3% deficit limit, as the deficit is considered 'temporary' and will decrease to 3% in 2024 and 2.8% in 2025 due to economic growth. However, the Commission warns that the Spanish government may still breach fiscal rules this year and exceed the spending ceiling set by the EU. The Commission will continue to monitor the situation and re-evaluate it in the fall. Spain is one of the 10 countries that exceeded the 3% deficit limit in 2023, but unlike France, Italy, Belgium, Hungary, Malta, Poland, and Slovakia, it will not face sanctions. The Commission's report states that the Spanish government's primary net national expenditure will increase by 3.8% this year, exceeding the EU's recommended ceiling of 2.6%. The government has committed to gradually phasing out energy subsidies, but the Commission criticizes that the planned savings will not be used entirely to reduce the deficit, which could also be considered another breach of fiscal rules.
